narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned how to do multivariable calculus and apply it.
I have developed my critical thinking skills greatly, learning how to apply multiple concepts and theories to solve one question with various dimensions.
Through the course, I gained a deeper understanding of multi variable calculus and its applications in the real world.
I learned a lot about multivariable calculus and its applications
I developed a lot of insight into visualizing solids by their equations, and I learned how to use many different integrals to determine characteristics about certain solids and functions.

This course covers the most essential components of calculus in 3 and 4 dimensions, working with vectors, planes, surfaces, and volumes. Strategies for evaluating line and surface integrals occupy most of the curriculum.
I learned about the main concepts of multivariable calculus and how to apply them to common problems.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I don't like the fact that it is taught by TFs, especially when you must pre-register for the course even when you don't know which TF will be teaching.

This class was a bit poorly laid out. The material was completely taught by the homework videos, so class time became boring and useless, since instead of expanding on the learned material, it simply repeated it in a more confusing manner.
I feel that students' engagement with the course is high dependent on the section they register for, and I believe that should not be the case.

The course was structured in an interesting way as we were required to watch videos covering the content that we would learn in lecture the night before. This was helpful to begin in understand the material, but unfortunately sometimes I felt the videos were much better at explaining the content than my lecture.

The pre-class videos were very helpful in providing an introduction to the content for the following class. I really felt like having that introduction made class easier to follow along. Considering that this course is the first experience to math in 3 dimensions, it was especially important to be able to take in information during class because the concepts were very new and a take a while to fully grasp.
The problem sets were too short and too difficult. Students would benefit more from problem sets that better simulate test questions and are more repetitive.
The videos and PSETs of this course were useful. The level of teaching during lectures was not great and definitely made me work harder outside of class compared to other sections.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: No, I would recommend taking ENAS 151.
I would not recommend this course to another student due to the experience that I had with instructors not being helpful about providing resources when needed.
I think that I would recommend this course to another student, but I would make sure that the student had an interest in math before. If not, Im not sure they would get the most out of the course.

I would recommend this course to other students, but I would encourage them to try out different instructors because there is a very big difference in teaching ability among the instructors. I would also advise that the student stays on top of the work from the beginning. Completing the problem sets while learning the material is the best strategy because the class is very fast-paced.
Take this course only if you need it for a pre-req.
I would recommend this course to any student that must learn the concepts of multivariable calculus. However, I would suggest against taking it unless it is a requirement.
